Water-related Disaster Management Policy and Programme: The key elements are:
* Formulation of a WID mitigation policy with reference to upstream, downstream linkages and the International Day for Natural Disaster Reduction (IDNDR) national action plans;
* Preparation of WID-related Acts, Regulations and management guidelines;
	* Enhancing the capacity of all WID-related institutions such as the MoHA (Ministry of Home Affairs), MoPE, DWIDP, DHM (Department of Hydrology and Meteorology), DSCWM (Department of Soil Conservation and Watershed Management).
	* Preparation of water-induced hazard maps;
	* Identification of critical areas by ground inspection on priority basis; and
	* Zoning of high-risk areas.
	* Establishment and activation of disaster forecasting and early warning systems, covering floods, extreme precipitation and drought;
	* Strengthening of CBOs, NGOs, INGOs, local authorities, professional societies for disaster management networking;
	* Promotion of regional and international cooperation in WID management:
	* Establishment and enhancement in cooperation with neighbouring countries in data exchange and information system;
	* Encouragement of joint investigation into the Glacial Lake Outburst Flood (GLOF) with China;
	* Promotion of international cooperation for flood forecasting and warning system.
	* Establishment of emergency supply warehouses for high-risk areas on central and regional basis;
	* Development and review of evacuation plans at regular interval, conducting of rehearsals/drills exercises with all key stakeholders at frequent intervals at different locations and providing training in rescue operations for identified groups;
	* Formation of standing committees to support search and rescue programme with necessary facilities at district as well as local level (vulnerable localities); and
	* Discouraging and restricting settlements in high-risk areas.

and local NGOs. DWIDP, as the lead coordinating agency for WID, will be involved in planning activities. The key elements are:
* Making preparations for emergency response, rescue and relief;
* Making arrangements and delivering disaster relief supplies;
* Identification and assignment of responsibilities to different organizations for handling relief and rehabilitation work;
* Planning for emergency shelter and feeding for victims; and
* Securing relief and rehabilitation funding.
* Strengthening the existing bilateral inundation-related committees;
* Formulation of inundation policies; and
* Enhancing exchange of data and information and promotion of formal as well as informal contacts at field level.
* Identification, prioritization and development of management plans for high-risk areas;
* Development of effective non-structural measures such as flood forecasting, warning, flood proofing and disaster preparedness;
* Implementation of mitigation measures such as afforestation and bio-engineering with peopleâs participation, involving CBOs/NGOs and womenâs groups for river bank protection and conservation of critical areas;
* Implementation of structural measures such as river dikes, spurs, check dams, trail improvement and embankment construction with the help of community groups;
* Disaster due to drought:
	* Identification of potential drought-prone areas; and
	* Preparation and implementation of a national plan to cope with droughts.

Integrated Programme for Irrigated Agriculture. The key activities are:
* Launch of groundwater projects (STWs and DTWs) in new areas;
* Design and implementation of crop intensification and diversification in irrigated areas;
* Formulation of project to pilot voluntary land consolidation activities in two districts;
* Strengthening of market improvement system for agricultural produce;
* Continuation, consolidation and expansion of groundwater monitoring programmes and enhancement of regulatory measures;
* Strong monitoring, evaluation and feedback of the NWP and APP activities incorporated in the department/Ministry with incentive and conduct policy-related studies to overcome hindrances encountered in irrigated agriculture, if any;

Integrated Programme for Irrigated Agriculture. The key activities are:
* Launch of groundwater projects (STWs and DTWs) in new areas;
* Design and implementation of crop intensification and diversification in irrigated areas;
* Formulation of project to pilot voluntary land consolidation activities in two districts;
* Strengthening of market improvement system for agricultural produce;
* Continuation, consolidation and expansion of groundwater monitoring programmes and enhancement of regulatory measures;
* Strong monitoring, evaluation and feedback of the NWP and APP activities incorporated in the department/Ministry with incentive and conduct policy-related studies to overcome hindrances encountered in irrigated agriculture, if any;
* Regular monitoring of groundwater for water level fluctuations and surface/groundwater quality and setting out standard for irrigation use; and
	* A centrally-managed pilot programme under MoAC/DoA in the command area of large irrigation systems greater than 15,000 ha.
	* Implementation of conjunctive use of surface and groundwater programmes in the existing command areas of irrigation projects in the terai;
	* Rehabilitation of FMISs;
	* Rehabilitation of agency managed irrigation schemes (AMISs);
	* Rehabilitation of AMISs for management transfer to WUAs;
	* Implementation of command area development (CAD) work in existing AMISs to increase cropping intensity;
	* Implementation of adequate drainage system programmes in water-logged and inundated areas;
	* Improvement of on-station research and on-farm water management;
	* Improvement of tertiary-level water management;
	* Raising of irrigation service fees (ISF) in joint managed/AMISs as per the Irrigation Policy 2060;
	* Improvement of on-farm water management in farmers' schemes through greater farmer participation;
	* Improvement of the existing database (and establishment in others) on irrigation water supply and consumption; irrigation delivery; groundwater use and water table fluctuations; service fee recovery, etc;
	* Introduction of irrigation water delivery in volumetric basis system in some pilot schemes where WUAs are involved; and
	* Improvement of management of mechanical plants for scheme maintenance and also use of private institutions for the maintenance of workshops.
	* Implementation of new surface water (SW) and groundwater (GW) irrigations projects in the hills and terai;
	* Expansion of micro-irrigation (such as drip irrigation system with water harvesting facilities, sprinkler system and treadle pumps, etc) for small farmers, including women farmers of the terai, hills and mountains for the development of livestock, agriculture crops and other cash crops;
	* Initiate multipurpose irrigation projects (with a hydroelectric generation component such as Bheri-Babai diversion, Sunkosi/Kamala diversion and West Rapti storage);
	* Groundwater exploration and investigation to support new GW projects.
	* Also groundwater recharge study developed as a programme;
	* Feasibility and investment studies of irrigation projects to verify their viability; and
	* Improvement of quality control in construction activities as well as work standards.

Programme to develop cost-effective micro, small and medium hydropower. The key activities are:
* Introducing  necessary steps to utilize and maximize local professional, financial, material, equipment and labour resources in hydropower projects;
* Developing programmes to identify cost-effective small and medium hydropower plants;
* Introducing and practising the âvalue engineeringâ concept in hydropower projects as far as possible;
* Developing small and medium size projects by mobilizing local resources;
* Reviewing the re-lending rate as appropriate for public sector projects; and
* Encouraging the development of projects to utilize the existing infrastructure such as transmission lines, access roads, etc.
* Expediting the INPS grid extension activities in peri-urban and terai rural areas;
* Supporting development and maintenance of isolated micro and small hydropower projects and alternative energy sources to extend hill and mountain rural electrification;
* Encouraging and supporting CBOs, including women's groups, to participate in electricity distribution programmes;
* Integrating cottage and agro-industry programmes with rural electrification;
* Supporting micro-hydro programmes and local initiatives;
* Establishing Rural Electrification Agency to expedite extension of rural electrification programmes;
* Mobilizing public participation and also establish Rural Electrification Fund; and
* Investing 1% royalty obtained from the hydropower projects in the hydropower infrastructure-affected VDCs for the sole purpose of expanding electrification to such VDCs.
* Carrying out power system planning and prepare hydropower expansion plans in a transparent manner;
* Encouraging suitable types of hydropower projects to address the present seasonal imbalances in supply and demand;
* Identifying and developing hydropower projects with due attention to regional balance; and
* Continuing demand-side management exercises and incorporate captive plants.

Programme to encourage private investments in hydropower development and electric power distribution. The key activities are:
* Establish an independent Electricity Regulatory Commission to create a conducive atmosphere to raise the confidence and attract private sector to invest in hydropower development;
* Create an effective 'one-window' entity to support private sector participation;
* Introduce levy on electricity consumption to generate more resources to the Power Development Fund, which has been created to encourage private investments; and
* Make appropriate arrangements to avail of the national transmission grid to wheel electric power as well as distribution of power direct to consumers by private producers.
* Restructuring the NEA through appropriate corporatization and ultimately privatizing it before 2027;
* Establishing Rural Electrification Agency at the centre to develop and support rural electrification programmes;
* Establishing Hydropower Research Centre and coordinate with other existing academic and research institutions;
* Implementing both technical and non-technical loss reduction programmes in power sector through effective institutional mechanisms and community participation; and
* Developing Electricity Tariff Fixation Commission as an independent regulatory body (Electricity Regulatory Commission).

Management of existing hydrological and meteorological network.
* Developing a programme to rehabilitate and equip the existing DHM stations;
* Developing the programme to full scale validation of hydrological and meteorological data;
* Setting up a hydraulic laboratory for proper and timely calibration of current metres;
* Regularizing publication of yearbooks by implementing Hydrological and Meteorological Information System (HIS);
* Establishing a network of water-related agencies to enhance coordination among agencies seeking hydrological and meteorological data.
	* Extend hydrological and meteorological networks:
	* DHM establishing temporary hydrometric stations in collaboration with water resources project developers;
	* Developing a programme to extend DHM networks addressing the pronounced orographic effects and install recorders with appropriate telemetry system.
	* Funding and management of hydrological and meteorological network:
	* Developing a collaborative support programme to finance the setting up and maintenance of hydro-meteorological stations;
	* Raising awareness among general public and legislators of the need for quality, timeliness and sufficient data so that cost-effective projects can be developed;
	* Exploring long-term external assistance to support the DHM activities; and
	* Exploring regional countriesâ assistance to support and maintain a weather forecasting and flood warning system.
	* Introducing the IWRM and river basin management principles in water resources policy(ies) and legislation;
	* Developing programmes to raise awareness of the advantages of IWRM among all stakeholders, general public, legislators, political activists, civil societies and professional societies;
	* WEC collecting, collating and segregating all relevant data and information on a river basin basis;
	* Encourage all data generators and providers to publish data on river basin basis; and
	* NPC and WEC requiring statements from sector programme developers to produce 'river basin water balance' prior to getting administrative approval for all projects and programmes.

Initiating river basin studies of priority basins;
* Develop and Implement DSS in water resources programmes:
* Establishment as well as strengthening of institutions for river basin planning:

Programme to appraise and understand the water-related needs of neighbouring countries. The key activities are:
* Establishing a cell at WEC to assess the regional water-related issues;
* Establishing a database, develop strategies and enhance negotiating capabilities;
* Assessing the electrical energy needs of the neighbouring countries;
* Exploring strategies and alternatives for water sharing, together with downstream benefits and navigational possibilities; and
* Exploring opportunities for enhancing regional cooperation in power sector.
* Expanding power exchange activity to 150 MW by 2007 and to 400 MW by 2017;
* Ratifying or amending the power trade agreement between Nepal and India;
* Promoting Track II and III interactions among basin countries;
* Improving the mechanism for data and information exchange; and
* Formulating a general framework of cooperation in development and management of trans-boundary rivers, including an agreement on downstream benefits.
* Forming Mahakali River Commission to implement the Pancheshwar Project;
* Activating the Nepal-India Joint Commission under the 1987 agreement;
* Reviewing and pursuing for compliance with the provisions of the Kosi and Gandak agreements;
* Pursuing the study and implementation of the Kosi High Dam and Sunkosi-Kamala Diversion Project, including navigational access to sea; and
* Exploring other multipurpose projects with bilateral or multilateral benefits.
